<DESCRIPT>  COLLEGE; SPORT; EDUCATION; STATISTIC  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A national survey on graduation rates shows that basketball players lag far
behind other athletes and the rest of the student body.;    Only 39 percent of
the basketball players from the 1984-85 freshmen class received degrees over a
five-year period. Football checked in at 47 percent.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BASKETBALL PLAYERS ARE TRAILING THE GRADUATION FIELD  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Sports Digest;  SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT (publ. 3/28/91, pg. 2D);  Because
of an error by the Associated Press, the eligibility status of NHL players for
the 1992 U.S. Olympic team was incorrect in Wednesday's editions. U.S. Coach
Dave Peterson said he would make use of any NHL players available, but he did
not expect many to be try out because of conflicts with their professional
teams' schedule.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Of the Final Four teams, Duke, at 95.9 percent, had the best overall
graduation rate. Las Vegas is the worst at 21.1 percent.; BASKETBALL: Las
Vegas forward Larry Johnson was selected player of the year and Kentucky's
Rich Pitino named coach of the year by the Sporting News. . . . Kenny
McCleary, a former Florida forward who played for the San Jose Jammers of the
Continental Basketball Association this season, signed a one-year contract
with an Australian team. . . . The NBA fined Indiana forward Chuck Person
$2,500 for kicking the ball into the stands during Saturday's game in Chicago.
Also fined: Los Angeles Lakers forward James Worthy, $1,500 for starting a
fight with Seattle's Sedale Threatt on Sunday. Threatt was fined $1,000.;
BOXING: The rematch between heavyweights Mike Tyson and Donovan "Razor"
Ruddock is scheduled June 28 in Las Vegas.; FOOTBALL: The agent for Raghib
"Rocket" Ismail of Notre Dame nows says he is considering a $6 million,
two-year offer to play for Toronto of the Canadian Football League. . . .
Linebacker Ned Bolcar, trying to rebound from knee surgery, is Miami's third
Plan B acquisition this year. He played in five games for Seattle last season
before hurting his knee. . . . Buffalo free safety John Hagy, a Plan B player,
signed with Houston, according to a television report.; TENNIS: San Jose's
Ryan Wolters, 14, gained the quarterfinals of the Boys' 14s at the Easter Bowl
tournament in Miami with a 6-1, 6-3 win over Kenneth Wasserman. . . . Ashley
Cooper, Ilie Nastase and Guillermo Vilas were named to the International
Tennis Hall of Fame. . . . Dexter McBride and Mitch Bridge defeated Matt
Woolridge of San Jose and Tim Wilkison in the doubles final of the USPTA
International Tennis Teacher Championship in Houston. . . . The Stanford
women's team, ranked second in the nation, defeated No. 3 Georgia 5-1 at
Stanford.; MISCELLANY: Las Vegas took over the lead in the 45th annual Western
Intercollegiate golf tournament in Monterey. The Rebels hold a six-stroke lead
over Oregon and Tulsa with a 36-hole score of 591. Oregon's Doug DuChateau
holds the individual lead at 143. The second round was played at Rancho
Canada's West Course. . . . Staci Wicklund and Jodi Solod of San Jose State
qualified for the NCAA Western Regional women's gymnastics meet April 6 in
Corvallis, Ore. . . . Mike Miller leads Darryl Bower by 56 pins after two
rounds of the Professional Bowlers Association's $200,000 National
Championship in Toledo, Ohio. . . . College players and foreign-based pros,
not NHL players, will be used on the 1992 U.S. Olympic hockey team, USA Hockey
announced.  </TEXT>
